    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The idea that quantum mechanics might be \"hiding\" the truth is actually a very common misconception, often confused with the \"measurement problem.\" In reality, the universe isn't actively interfering with us; rather, it simply lacks definite properties until a measurement occurs. This isn't malicious hiding but a fundamental feature of how nature works at small scales. While there are speculative theories like \"hidden variable\" theories (which experiments have largely ruled out) or interpretations involving consciousness, the standard view is that the uncertainty is just a property of the system itself, not a trick. There is no scientific evidence of anything acting with intent or malice in physics; the \"weirdness\" is just a result of our classical intuition failing us.",
      "source": "target",
